example.p:
Our only concern is if this set, along with the definitions of two operations, fulfills the ten properties of .  Let us check associativity of vector addition ().  For all \vect{u},\,\vect{v},\,\vect{w}\in Z,
                \vect{u}+(\vect{v}+\vect{w})
                &=\vect{z}+(\vect{z}+\vect{z})
                &=\vect{z}+\vect{z}
                &=(\vect{z}+\vect{z})+\vect{z}
                &=(\vect{u}+\vect{v})+\vect{w}
            .

solution.p:
Let us consider the existence of a zero vector, as required by  of a vector space.  The regular zero vector fails, (remember that the property must hold for every vector, not just for some),\colvector{x\\y}+\colvector{0\\0} = \colvector{y\\x}\ne\colvector{x\\y}.  Is there another vector that fills the role of the zero vector?  Suppose that \zerovector=\colvector{z_1\\z_2}.  Then for any vector \colvector{x\\y}, we have
                    \colvector{x\\y}+\colvector{z_1 \\z_2}
                    &= \colvector{y + z_2\\x + z_1}
                    =  \colvector{x\\y}
                so that x = y + z_2 and y = x + z_1.  This means that z_1 = y - x and z_2 = x - y.  However, since x and y can be any complex numbers, there are no fixed complex numbers z_1 and z_2 that satisfy these equations.  Thus, there is no zero vector,  does not hold, and the set \complex{2} with the proposed operations is not a vector space.

statement.p:
Consider the following sets of 3 \times 3 matrices, where the symbol * indicates the position of an arbitrary complex number.  Determine whether or not these sets form vector spaces with the usual operations of addition and scalar multiplication for matrices.

All matrices of the form \begin{bmatrix} * & * & 1\\ * & 1 & *\\ 1 & * & * \end{bmatrix}

All matrices of the form \begin{bmatrix} * & 0 & *\\ 0 & * & 0\\ * & 0 & * \end{bmatrix}

All matrices of the form \begin{bmatrix} * & 0 & 0\\ 0 & * & 0\\ 0 & 0 & * \end{bmatrix} (These are the diagonal matrices.) 

All matrices of the form \begin{bmatrix} * & * & *\\ 0 & * & *\\ 0 & 0 & * \end{bmatrix} (These are the upper triangular matrices.)
